<font color="#FF0000">COMMENTS, STORIES SINCE THEWAR</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 13 12:13:01 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Spatz, I have answered your questions, but not the way you wanted them answered and that is what bothers you.<br>
I had answered your questions until you called me a baby-killer and as you have once again in this tread a murderer. I have chosen not to be victimized by shrinks a berry. <br>
When I first read those words from you I realized a few things.<br><br>
1.   That, you still believe vets to be baby killers and murderers after months of dialog with them, and you had learned nothing, about vets. <br>
2.    That, you're not a Doctor<br>
3. That you are in fact a phony psychologist <br>
4. You are not a shrink 4 me<br>
5. You have been deceiving individuals on this web site for months.<br><br>
Many that had posted here seemed to have agreed with you that Vietnam was wrong, and you built upon that, but I came along and did not. That bothered you.<br>
I do not believe the purpose of the Vietnam war to have been wrong.<br>
I do believe we fought it wrong, but the primary principles under which I went to fight there was not wrong. <br>
You chose to believe otherwise and choose to seek other avenues, that decision has now have come back to haunt you. That is why, 30 years later the jungles of Vietnam are exciting to you. Why? <br>
I have been a professional counselor since 1972, and yes I do have my master's degree in a related field. That is why my words to you are worded the way they are. They have already caused you sleepless nights and the way you post and respond reveals that. spatz you're fighting even now, to remove that mask you have been hiding under all these years and it really hurts you inside. <br>
You see barry when I went to Nam, the war was still popular, and the majority of the American people supported it. I went there for all the right reasons, at the right time. I fought for all the right reasons. When I was there I felt the support of the American people and that was an honor. Demonstrations that began at home during that time were being met with counter demonstrations by those who supported the American fighting men and what we were doing in Vietnam.  <br>
When your time came, you choose to fight the draft, but the hidden fear within you was the primary motivating agency that propelled you to become a conscientious objector. You feared that you would be send to Nam and you would die there. You have posted that information yourself. So why did you become a CO? For fear, spatz, plain and simple as soon as you admit that and come to grips with it, the sooner you will face a future without fear.<br><br>
When I came home things had changed; the home atmosphere was different. But, I was not met with demonstrators at the gate; I was met with silence and a country that was in transition. <br>
The draft dodgers, conscientious objectors, long hair freaky people, social misfits had all joined a mass hyena pack that amounted to massive national social unrest. <br>
About that time I joined the police force and guess what? I fought those demonstrators on the streets of LA, during the riots of the early 70's. Among the pamphlets and literature I found being passed out by those demonstrators against the war and the US Government, were pamphlets that stated the same type of statements I had found along the trails of the jungles of Vietnam. They even seemed to have been printed by the same cheap underground press that was used in Hanoi. That told me a lot. That American was being deceived and destroyed from within. And that those fighting against the war and yes I did lump them all together, after all they were all together in the hyena packs on 1st street and Los Angeles Street in 1972. It was pure communist propaganda leaflets they were distributing similar to what I had seen in Vietnam and I saw no difference. <br>
I went on with my life, proud to have served in the midst of individuals that did not understand that pride. But I kept silent until I found my diary and began to rewrite it into book form, As I shared that with others, many saw what I saw, saw a different Vietnam; a Vietnam not polluted by the political injustice there and here at home. A war that should have been fought and won the way we were fighting in 1967-1968 and they wanted to hear that side of the story.<br>
 <br>
You also mentioned that if you had met us (vets) in the jungles you would have pulled the trigger. Spatz you're the type of individual I probably would have shot myself in Nam, because if words can anger you so, you would have pulled the trigger on innocent women, children and old men in Nam. You would have been one of those giving their &quot;Winter Soldiers Testimony,&quot; about what an unjust war it was, because of the guilt you would have felt. You would have been there for all the wrong reasons. <br><br>
You remind me of a story about a Jewish fellow I had read about, seems like Israel was going to war, but some of the people who were with this soldier were going to war for all the wrong reason. Their hearts were not right, So this Jewish commander I don't know what rank he was, said to them. <br>
'Whoever is afraid and trembling, let him return and depart from us. So the majority of them were allowed to depart and not go to battle. But still many of the people remained and this presented a problem in a limited war. It seems the draft had produced too many of them, they were individuals who had no real concept about why the war was being fought. So a simple test was initiated. The men were then taken down to a river and tested there. Those who went down to the river and who lapped the water with their tongue, as a dog laps, as well as everyone who knelt to drink were disqualified. <br>
Now the number of those who lapped, putting their hand to their mouth, was 300 men; Those became Gideon's army and they went to war and prevailed. <br>
spatz, you were given the opportunity but as you have said you were afraid and trembled and so the good old US government allowed you to depart from the war just like those Jewish people were thousands of years ago. No one though of them as wrong, they were honest about their fear and trembling. It's evident from all of your postings that you feared and trembled and that's not what I have a problem with. <br>
Guess what spatz, I feared and trembled all the time I was in Nam. But I drank my water with my hand, I looked at the war and to me it was just and I wanted to go. I volunteered to go and I don't regret it one bit. I did not allow my fear to prevent me from doing what I believed to be right. <br>
You did and that is what bothers you today, and to disguise that fear you have chosen to attack those that did go to war, by calling them murderers and baby killers. <br>
You have tried to make yourself a VietSON, a Vietnam brother, but you choose a different road and cannot belong. Sometimes it is a &quot;Viet thing&quot; and you don't belong nor can you ever belong to it. That's why you'll always be excluded from joining the VFW, you can never understand because you choose to travel a different road and that's ok.<br>
What is wrong is that you have tried to justify it for all the wrong reason. Now 30 years later you have to deal with your conscience, your own conscience is objecting to what your mind has told your heart all these years. <br>
You can never build a bridge between the two of us, I fought what I believe to be a just war, you're still trying to justify your actions. I would not embrace you because you stood against individuals that died honrably because they believed in American and in what we were doing in Vietnam. It's as if those Jewish people would have returned and scoured Gideon for going to war. <br>
Spatz if you have helped so many, what did you say, 400 cops to get out of the system, spatz then you turned them into causalities of another war. How many of those individuals are now leading productive lives? You've turned them in to basket cases, and destroyed their human dignity. Made them victims of Vietnam and that gave you power and helped to justify your stand. If you did as you claim to have done so, you caused a lot a grief; pain and suffering to those that did go to war. I know because I've had to counsel with those who had been deceived into accepting a guilt trip by individuals like you, all because they served their country with honor and were never recognized by their country for doing so. Instead they were further victimized by individuals like you. <br>

